Title: Kestrel
Type: Character
Source: V4

===

~ The Order's former war leader. Imprisoned for a decade. Has spent ten years constructing a picture of Silas's betrayal from incomplete evidence.

She plays both sides from behind bars — tipping off the Alderman, steering Fleur toward the fire, engineering the coronation as her revenge. Her reversal at the climax is not redemption but reckoning: she undoes her own work, and in doing so finally reads the evidence correctly.

A decade of captivity has sharpened her into something blade-like — perceptive, strategic, and hungry. She is not broken. She is honed. Her misreading of Silas has hardened into certainty: Silas took the Book, found an heir, built a private lineage. The betrayal she has been living inside for ten years has a second layer.

She is wrong. She has been wrong for ten years. When she finally reads the training gaps in Fleur correctly — every absence the outline of Kestrel herself — the picture she has carried collapses. What's left is harder and more true.

Her choice in Act III is not redemption. It is reckoning. She engineered this. She undoes it. Those are not the same thing as being forgiven.
